Layer-2

MegaETH Making Ethereum Great Again

Kunal Goel

Sep 9, 2024   12 min read

Key Insights

  • MegaETH aims for 100,000 transactions per second with 1 ms block times, pushing blockchain performance to rival Web 2.0 applications.
  • It is designed as an L2 solution that uses a massive, highly optimized sequencer but inherits Ethereums security and decentralization to offer a scalable solution without the usual compromises.
  • MegaETHs architecture allows for real-time applications like fully onchain gaming and decentralized exchanges, unlocking new possibilities.
  • The project's ambitious goals come with significant execution risks. The public testnet is expected in Q4 2024, and the mainnet in early 2025.
  • If successful, MegaETH could set new standards for Layer-2 scalability, forcing the rest of the ecosystem to adapt.

In an era when the market has growing infrastructure fatigue, MegaETH, an upcoming Layer-2 (L2) on Ethereum, has captured its attention with its incredibly lofty vision. MegaETH boasts an impressive throughput of more than 100,000 transactions per second (TPS) with block times of less than one millisecond. If MegaETH successfully delivers this performance in a real-world environment, it would be a 10-20x improvement in throughput and a >100x improvement in latency over existing Layer-1 (L1) and Layer-2 solutions. Unsurprisingly, MegaETH brands itself as the first "real-time blockchain".

This report explores how modern blockchain design has converged on a model that overcomes the blockchain trilemma and why MegaETHs architectural choices position it as a potential leader in achieving this "endgame" design. We will delve into the key design features that allow MegaETH to maximize throughput without compromising on decentralization or security, and how its innovative approach could set a new benchmark for Layer-2 solutions in the blockchain space.

Endgame Blockchain Design

Blockchain design philosophy in 2024 has primarily converged on a model combining centralized block production with decentralized block validation, allowing blockchains to overcome "the blockchain trilemma." This architecture provides scalability through a small group of high-performance block producers while ensuring security and decentralization through a broad network of validators. Despite advancements, no blockchain system has yet fully realized this endgame design.

MegaETH is the maximally performant realization of this vision. It uses a single massive, highly optimized sequencer to achieve the highest throughput and lowest latency of any blockchain. By leveraging Ethereum for settlement and EigenDA for data availability (DA), MegaETH benefits from their decentralization and crypto-economic security guarantees.

Mega Design

Until blockchains achieve the endgame design, they must make the general tradeoff between scalability and decentralization, where better and more expensive hardware increases scalability but limits decentralization and vice versa. Strict improvements are possible by improving hardware efficiency and adding new infrastructure like light clients and L2s.

Ethereum has moved to a more efficient curve through its L2s. However, even now, popular L2s only outcompete alt-L1s on decentralization, not scale. A key reason is that most L2s plan to decentralize their sequencers in the future and, as such, limit their node hardware to allow for multiple sequencers to run and coordinate.

MegaETH disagrees with this approach. It pushes execution on the L2 to its highest theoretical limit, constrained only by hardware.

  • MegaETHs sequencer runs on significantly more performant and expensive hardware than even alt-L1 validator nodes. While better hardware generally allows for proportionately better performance, MegaETHs sequencer is so significantly beefier that it unlocks Web2-like capabilities that have never been possible in crypto. A prominent example is MegaETHs 1-4 TB sequencer RAM, which can hold the entire state in memory, allowing it to execute transactions without interacting with storage.
  • MegaETH will only ever run on a single concurrent sequencer, eliminating the need for consensus during normal execution. Consensus requires multiple nodes to coordinate, increasing latency as information travels between them. A single sequencer with sub-second block times makes MegaETH a real-time blockchain.
  • Just beefing up the hardware is not enough. MegaETH is working on multiple software improvements to achieve the highest performance per hardware unit. These include optimizing the EVM, implementing parallel execution, and creating a more efficient data structure for updating the global state.

Mega Centralization?

An alt-L1 with such extreme hardware requirements would be highly centralized. However, MegaETH's choice of an L2 architecture allows it to inherit security and decentralization from the L1 and data availability (DA) layers.

At launch, MegaETH plans to be an optimistic L2 on Ethereum which will use EigenDA for data availability. An optimistic L2 with working fraud proofs, DA, and an escape hatch provides users with a secure fallback against a malicious single sequencer.

Security

  • As an optimistic L2, MegaETHs sequencer must post a bond on Ethereum that can be slashed through a fraud-proof if it posts an invalid transaction. This mechanism provides a cryptoeconomic guarantee to MegaETHs users against a malicious sequencer.
  • The escape hatch is a mechanism for withdrawing funds to the base layer without interacting with the L2. If the sequencer fails, is unavailable for an extended period, or a malicious upgrade is planned, the escape hatch allows users to withdraw funds to the base layer without needing the sequencer.

Censorship Resistance

  • Centralized block building is more prone to censorship, a challenge even Ethereum faces. MegaETH plans to rotate sequencers among different parties and geographies to minimize the risk.
  • The L2 architecture also inherits some censorship resistance from Ethereum, as transactions censored by the L2 sequencer can be forced through the base layer. However, there is typically a time delay for forced transaction inclusion, so this ensures only eventual censorship resistance, not real-time censorship resistance.

Mega Thesis

MegaETH aims to be the first blockchain to deliver the endgame design, achieving scalability with fewer trade-offs than other high-performance blockchain systems. Although built on a decentralized, modular stack, MegaETH possesses the capability of an integrated blockchain.

Relatively Better

The easiest case for MegaETH is to compare it to other popular blockchain designs.

Compared to Alt-Layer-1s

  • MegaETH will outcompete alt-L1s on scalability as it implements an even faster node with no consensus overhead.
  • Additionally, because it uses the L2 design, it can inherit the decentralization of the Ethereum base layer.
  • As such, it may be considered strictly superior to the alt-L1 design. However, practically, L2s have the training wheels of upgradability and security councils that add trust assumptions.

Compared to Popular Layer-2s

  • The most popular L2s, such as Arbitrum, Base, and Optimism, currently have a centralized sequencer, so MegaETHs choice of a more performant one does not add further trust assumptions.
  • The path to greater scale for other L2s requires solving a more complicated chain abstraction roadmap for coordination and block proposal. MegaETHs path to launch seems relatively more straightforward.
  • However, small L2s with decentralized sequencers may eventually provide greater liveness guarantees.

Compared to High-Performance Layer-2s

  • Other L2s, like Eclipse and Movement, also have a high-throughput design. However, they both plan to decentralize their sequencers, limiting their eventual scale.
  • Additionally, MegaETHs choice of utilizing the EVM gives it access to the breakthroughs in proving made by other EVM-based L2s.
  • EVM compatibility also gives MegaETH access to a much larger pool of crypto-native developers, applications, and tooling.
  • However, alt-VMs may be better engineered for high-throughput execution.

Absolutely Great

MegaETHs key proposition is that the beefy centralized sequencer delivers performance similar to Web 2.0. Vitalik Buterin, who invested in MegaETH, called it AWS with blockchain scaffolding. As such, the absolute case is even stronger.

Real-Time Blockchain

A single sequencer with a 1 ms block time means that MegaETH's applications have no extra overhead. Any interaction with a MegaETH application would seem similar to interacting with a Web 2.0 application to the user, as there is almost no delay for a block to be constructed. This reduced latency unlocks what is possible in the application design space, like fully onchain gaming, fully onchain order book exchanges, decentralized VPNs, and more.

Unlimited Scale

MegaETH executes transactions through a single sequencer, with throughput constrained only by its hardware. There is no overhead from consensus messages bouncing around different nodes. As such, it may be the only blockchain that truly scales with Moores law. MegaETH claims it will have a throughput of 100,000+ real transactions per second at launch. This throughput unlocks elusive crypto applications such as onchain social media.

Budding Ecosystem

MegaETHs ambitious vision has caught the attention of the crypto community. MegaETH is incubating an ecosystem of new application builders called the MegaMafia. While specific information remains limited, early projects building on MegaETH include:

  • HQ Trivia-style social app by Arthur Shir
  • Fully onchain perp DEX, Valhalla
  • Spot DEX, GTE
  • Decentralized VPN, Hop
  • Real-time prediction market, Doxa

Strong Founders and Backers

MegaETHs founders have both technical and crypto-native expertise:

  • CEO: Yilong Li, CS PhD from Stanford
  • CTO: Lei Yang, PhD from MIT
  • CBO: Shuyao Kong, MBA from Harvard, former Head of Business Development at Consensys
  • Head of Growth: Namik Muduroglu, BS from NYU, formerly at Consensys and Hypersphere Ventures

MegaETHs $20 million seed round was led by Dragonfly Capital and included prominent investors such as Vitalik Buterin, Joseph Lubin, Cobie, and others.

Mega Impact on Broader Ecosystem

The case for MegaETH seems clear, but if it successfully delivers on its promise, it can have a massive impact across the crypto ecosystem.

Ethereum, EVM, and Modularity

Under the Demand for Security Model, growth in Ethereums L2 ecosystem directly improves ETHs fundamentals. Additionally, MegaETHs research toward making the EVM more performant will likely accelerate Ethereums own technical roadmap.

While modularity is growing across the crypto ecosystem, MegaETHs performance is only possible on Ethereum as its L2. This is because MegaETH is reliant on the Ethereum base layer remaining extremely decentralized so that it can work off a single centralized sequencer.

Other Layer-2s

MegaETH will likely have knock-on effects on other L2s, who will have to innovate to compete on performance. Healthy competition is likely to accelerate growth whether on their own planned roadmaps or by pivoting to a more MegaETH-like design.

If MegaETHs stack is fully open-source, L2s may also directly benefit from the research and development by the MegaETH team.

EigenDA

MegaETH plans to use EigenDA and will likely be one of its prominent customers. If EigenDA is able to service MegaETHs significant DA demand, it will be a strong indicator of its scale and capabilities.

Mega Risks and Limitations

MegaETH is pretty good, but it is not perfect.

High Execution Risk

MegaETH has a bold design and bolder claims. While its design choices have a theoretical basis, there may be many a slip until implementation. Beyond implementing the big sequencer, significant improvements must be in other areas before it can be live. MegaETH lists significant challenges with building such a high-throughput blockchain.

MegaETH reportedly has a private testnet and aims to have a public testnet in early Q4 2024, with the mainnet launch in early Q1 2025.

Modular Security Guarantees

MegaETH will use Ethereum for settlement and EigenDA for data availability. As such, it qualifies as an optimistic validium.

  • An optimistic L2 has crypto-economic security up to the size of the bond posted by the sequencer. ZK designs are generally considered more secure because they rely on cryptographic security.
  • As a validium, MegaETH is secured by the crypto-economic guarantees of the EigenDA nodes. If they maliciously withhold data or are unable to provide data due to a bug, MegaETH users' funds may get frozen. A rollup using Ethereum for DA is considered superior as it inherits the full security of Ethereums validators.

MegaETH plans to move to a zero-knowledge architecture in the future; however, it is unclear if Ethereum DA will ever have sufficient capacity for MegaETH.

Ecosystem Risk

MegaETHs scale is so much higher than that of other blockchains that it requires an entirely new stack of supporting infrastructure to be built. This includes RPCs, block explorers, wallets, and indexers. MegaETH is building some part of this stack internally while also engaging other teams to build it for them.

Half-Full Nodes

MegaETH has an extremely performant sequencer. It does not expect that its full nodes will be able to keep up with transaction execution and expects them to merely record the updated state. Sequencer honesty and proper execution are ensured through fraud proofs.

However, this design means that entities like exchanges that receive deposits on MegaETH can be assured of correctness and trustlessly credit deposits only at the end of the challenge period (typically seven days). There are ways for these entities to mitigate this risk, through insurance or investing in their own beefy nodes that can perform execution, but that may increase risks and/or costs.

State Growth, MEV Centralization, and Other Unsolved Problems

MegaETH faces some of the same unsolved challenges as other fast blockchains, perhaps even more because of its extreme choices. These challenges include state growth, which degrades performance, and MEV centralization, which may worsen user experience. MegaETH does not claim to have solved these.

Mega Leap Forward

MegaETH represents a massive leap toward achieving the blockchain endgame of combining scalability with decentralization. With its singular focus on performance, MegaETH pushes throughput limits, enabling real-time blockchain applications comparable to Web 2.0 experiences. However, its ambitious goals come with considerable execution risks, especially as it prepares for its mainnet launch in early 2025. The success of MegaETH will depend on its ability to overcome these challenges and deliver on its bold vision of reshaping the Layer-2 landscape for Ethereum.
